entries.femaleVariant: I'll have a drink.
What's happening in the area?
How're you holding up?
I'll have a drink.
Anything interesting happening in the area?
"Interesting?" Around here?
How do you feel?
I lost my son. How am I supposed to feel?
I did like you said. I invited her over for dinner.
And...?
She's so skinny... Who would've thought.
Did you talk to Misty?
I know what she looks like. That's not what I'm asking.
<mothertongue l="mex" m="¿excéntrica?" b="Hmm. She's a little bit... " a="? Said my home sits on a natural energy source."/>
Did you ever talk to Misty in the end?
But I think I know why Jackie...
She's a nice girl. We exchanged numbers.
<kiroshi l="mex" o="Ahí viene." t="Coming right up." b="" a=""/>
I don't even have his body.
I'm sorry, V. I shouldn't have... I-It's just...
They say that funerals are for the living, not for the dead.
When I see him that day... in that limo, all covered in blood – you know what I wanted to say to him?
<mothertongue l="mex" m="«Te metiste en un gran problema, Jackie Welles»." b="" a=" As if he was fourteen years old again – just coming home from a fight with the other kids."/>
It's like... my brain was trying to protect me from what I was always afraid would happen.
<mothertongue l="mex" m="¡Mi propio hijo!" b="How can I say goodbye if I can't even give him a proper funeral? " a=""/>
It's OK, Mama Welles.
I-I can't talk about this now, OK?
Heh, not one single thing. That's why the kids, they join gangs. No jobs. No future. And where they end up?
This neighborhood die a long time ago.
Behind bars, or in the ground.
Gotta go.
